Hello Karen,
In addition to the suggestions made by Wolfgang and James, I would like to check the (log-)likelihood profile of the between-district heterogeneity (sigma^2.1 in your case). Wolfgang's metafor provides a convenient function for this purpose, the syntax looks like: profile(step1,sigma2=1).

If you got a bell-shaped curve in the profile likelihood plot, it indicates that the variance component is identifiable in your current model structure. More precisely, visually check whether the plot is peaked at the point estimate of the between-district heterogeneity (in this case, 0) and whether the curve decreases quickly as the value of the variance component deviates from the point estimate. This can give you an idea of how well the model is able to estimate the variance component based on the data and the model structure.


Best,
Yefeng Yang




